>>114386261
Depends, for 98% of metal? Basically almost no crossover. Anything to do with NeoCLASSICAL metal (shred)? Yeah thats going to flirt with literal classical A LOT, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JtjOe5e9VFA.

You obviously have shred's slightly retarded brother - power metal. Which is going to sound classical inspired due to being related to shred, sometimes even doing their own cheesy cover pieces lol https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W8bbodUFUUU

Dissonant metal is another genre very obviously inspired by atonal and romantic composers of the 20th century. Stuff like this https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4xo9eVty8jM is probably kind of close to being straight up transcribe-able into a classical piece, close to Jason Becker's track "Air" which to me was literally classical. Ehnahre/Kayo Dot and such is another example of stuff very close to classical in the disso format. A lot of artists in this genre will literally list classical artists as influences, or in Luc Lemay's case, he went to school and has literally written classical pieces (that I don't think he has ever published, but has mentioned in interviews).

Prog obviously has its moments too, but it depends on what direction they are taking, sometimes its prog in a classical direction or in a jazzy direction.

Having just spent the better part of the last year fucking around in the far reaches of this in order to finish up, polish up, and help score about a dozen albums I'm involved in, and become a better musician/bassist... (Oh god...)

There are certain tricks in classical and jazz that are almost everywhere because of how functional they are - basics like
>Placing tonic->subdominant->dominant->tonic functionalities (in roughly that order) in chord progressions, no matter how buried they get in the riff
>Flat fifth substitutions to increase tension but keep the functionality of chords - even if most of the chord is implied
>Leading up to, or just straight up using and abusing (v, V, viiº, vii, VII) a dominant-functioning chord in relation to what comes next allows you to make smooth modulations across leaps that would sound like jagged shit otherwise
>Jumping up 1-4 semitones with the same riff sounds like a resolution. Jumping down the same amount increases tension, begging for resolution afterward.

>Can confirm
The music doesn't have a whole lot to do with Dream Theater or Rush... There are always going to be little hints because I love both bands, but once the introduction and character building's done, there really aren't very many softer moments that aren't there explicitly to be dark as fuck.

>No throw-away moments
I had to fight every single band on this. If an entire album is just blistering all the way through, nothing stands out. You fill the reprieves with hooks, and revisit those hooks later to keep them from being complete throwaways, but those reprieves have to be there or there's no dynamic.

>Black metal
It's more Satanic Temple-ish, pointing the finger in great detail at the holy wars fought between the "Spawn of Abraham." The cover hasn't been 100% nailed down (and it needs to be, shit's supposed to hit the presses soon), but the main contender's a charcoal drawing that kind of reminds me of Saturn Devouring his Son.

>Pirate metal
That's exactly what I mean... although one might wind up with a pirate-themed drinking song that sadly wound up with a metric ass-load of my best turns of phrase.

>10+ minute song
The rock operas all do, and one of them is written so that everything flows into the next piece seamlessly and there are callbacks all over the place - it's basically a 60 minute song that's going to be followed up by a 20-30 minute EP from the antagonist's POV. The black metal project has one 11 minute thing, and the whole thing's probably going to be laid out in chapters "Chapter 1: These dickheads take a disliking to these other dickheads." "Chapter 2: The other dickheads discover gunpowder."

>>114389053
No. 3 is an odd one so I can understand why you'd feel that. Usually in a concerto grosso, in the first movement there's solo parts for a smaller group of solo instruments and in between those solo parts there's the tutti parts, where the whole orchestra plays a main theme. But in No. 3 it's just a string ensemble (3 violins, 3 violas, 3 cellos and continuo) playing both solo and tutti parts, removing the usual clear loud/soft contrast. In a way it makes it sound more 'Bach-like' with the instruments just 'chugging along' in a Fortspinnung-like manner. There's also the strange second adagio movement that's just one measure (!) long, making the whole piece almost seem like some modernist experiment.

posts.com:
So since the 00s to now has seen Western pop music transition from rock 'n roll as the standard genre, do you think that progressive rock will see more representation in the dedicated rock scene?

You don't get nearly the disregard or disdain for experimental jazz, classical, bop, folk by traditional fans that you get in rock. I feel that mostly comes from people who grew up with pop and rock like it was peanut butter and jelly and mainly followed pop, so whatever prog they encountered would've been seen as a mistake in rock, rather than a subgenre that didn't pander to their tastes.

Now that rock is increasingly seen as passe in contemporary media, people growing up from the 00s onward are going to be increasingly detached from rock of they only follow what is mainstream (which nearly every music enjoyer does until they hit the age of self-discovery). So people will start treating rock increasingly like jazz and other branches of music that aren't predominant - something people have to seek out to experience rather than be passively exposed and conditioned to, so they go in with curiosity and a more open mind.

I bet you good money that the jojo-fan influx in the '10s was just as much driven by the above as it was memes.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
I feel like there's two different crowds when it comes to defining progressive rock.

Traditionalists who claim that progressive rock is a genre with a distinct sound, specifically the bands from the late 1960s and 1970s, and all prog rock and its subgenres from the 80s onwards are derived from, influenced by, and brached out from 70s progressive rock.

And others that claim that "progressive rock" is more of a philosophy or an approach to rock music rather than a genre that started in the 60s and 70s, but isn't bound to a very specific sound and that's why you'll see experimental, noisy, mathy, jazzy, extreme, dissonant, artsy or technical groups with complex time signatures and volatile song structures get labelled prog even if they sound nothing like the 70s bands.

>>114383793
I wouldn’t call the former group traditionalists or purists. The latter philosophy was dominant throughout the emergence and heyday of prog rock and most progressive artists, and I’d also image most of their fans, did not view prog rock so narrowly. Progressive music traditionally meant anything that challenged rules and pushed boundaries, and confining any music to a few small values based on the most superficial stereotypes of its most popular artists would have been counterintuitive to the whole progressive idea in the 1960s and 70s. By definition, there were no “traditionalists” in prog.

>>114378662
Musically and production-wise, it's incredible - powerful, dark, innovative.

Lyrically, it falls short. There are moments of brilliance, but far too often it simply retreads well-worn hip hop cliches - name dropping designer brands, objectifying women, braggadocio.

It's difficult for me to take the album seriously as real art when Kanye repeatedly sabotages his own songs with such shallow idiocy.

To give an example, New Slaves (one of the best songs on the album) starts off so promisingly, with concise imagery illustrating just how recent Jim Crow was and biting social commentary about how even successful blacks remain victims of racist assumptions -

>My mama was raised in the era when
>Clean water was only served to the fairer skin
>Doin' clothes, you woulda thought I had help
>But they wasn't satisfied unless I picked the cotton myself
>You see it's broke nigga racism
>That's that "Don't touch anything in the store"
>And it's rich nigga racism
>That's that "Come in, please buy more"

- but by the end of the song, Kanye has resorted to shallow racial grievance, indulging in a sexual revenge fantasy about fucking his white oppressor's wife in the Hamptons -

>Fuck you and your Hampton house
>I'll fuck your Hampton spouse
>Came on her Hampton blouse
>And in her Hampton mouth

This is truly vile stuff, and comes from the same place of hatred and sexual objectification that prompts drives a disproportionate number of black men to rape white women. Not only is it vile, it is also ironic, because it illustrates how Kanye's thoughts and desires are still dictated by the racist ideology he claims to be resisting - here and elsewhere in the album, it is clear Kanye has internalized the idea that his own people are inferior, and that only by fucking a white woman can he prove his equality to white men.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114380225
Similarly, even while calling out corporate America for targeting rich black Americans as suckers who will spend their money unscrupulously, Kanye is unable to let go of the delusion that his emancipation lies in the acquisition of luxury goods and status. He can't help but want to be included in the exclusive club of the Hamptons, just as in "Niggas in Paris" he couldn't help bragging about being a nigger in Paris. At the heart of these boasts is a desire to be accepted into the very white society he criticizes as oppressive and racist.

Throughout the songs, there is a dizzying list of brand name products - Porsche, Black Berry, Range Rover, iPhone, IBN diamond, Mercedes Benz.

What I'm describing is endemic to supposedly "serious" hip hop, and it really inhibits my ability to take it seriously. For a genre often described as "conscious," it seems very lacking in self-awareness.

In any case, I sincerely wish her luck and hope she finds a global audience who treasures her.

posts.sub: Sample audio from the movie Leon the Profession is featured in what electronic song?
posts.com:

posts.name: mooseman224

>>114357255
a common rhythm, especially with hip-hop and modern drum patterns, is having your kick on the one and a snare, clap or other mid range perc on the 2 and 4. Building out from there should be a good place to start. Starting with a bass is up to you. Try different things and you'll eventually find what works.

>if I don't choose decisively a genre, is the sound design and choice of instruments going to be a monstrous frankenstein clusterfuck?

Not necessarily. A lot of it will come down to experimentation and trying different combinations

When i started to make music i was very young. I used some shitty music tool for the playstation one. I had no idea about mastering and did the mastering basiclley right in the creation process.
Later on when i learned about mastering i still had my workflow on doing it with each sample right in the creation. This gave me a lot of headroom later on when doing the final mastering nowadays, ending up always with a kick that has too much energy.

In my shitty opinion, mastering is very important and can bring forth the real structure of the idea of an creation but you have to be very carefull. A low frequency rumbling around can become very loude when you go to the final mastering.

I keep continuing to master my samples right in the mix, keeping in mind how it might end up in the final stage when doing the (somewhat second) mastering.

When i watch someone else lifestream i see them doing a lot of comprasion in the mastering, something i never really needed to do.

>I-IV-V
Technically the correct roman numerals, but they need to be lower case because this is in a minor key. That's something you'll want to know if you ever want to use chord symbols like that to communicate with other musicians. And it matters because many songs use borrowed chords. If you're in the key of C:
>I-IV-V
C - F - G
>i-iv-v
Cm - Fm - Gm
>I-iv-v-IV
C - Fm - Gm - F

>>114364524
long everything, long releases, long reverbs, effects that dont hurt to hear for a long time. it always sounds so stupid to say but you do sort of have to just feel out how to take something and evolve it in a way you want it to but i guess thats advice for all kinds of music isnt it. you can try automating bpm to make it have less of a direct effect on the speed of your track because itll be constantly changing.

note holders are also pretty cool, see if the plugins you like have those and if they dont you might be able to get one in ur daw. they let you take things really slow while keeping them evolved. if you have keyboard with dials you can assign them to various aspects of a synth patch like wavetable position or fm amount or anything and then adjust those slowly. i guess there isnt really one specific way to make any kind of music and be guaranteed that it'll turn out exactly how you wanted it.

buying tips:
test it out first. music stores have a PC so you can

white buttons should be bright white. if yellow a smoker owned it.

tap finger pads as light as you once you find the lightest touch to register go around all 4 edges of each pad noting any spots where a light touch wont register (pads light up when a hit registers)

knobs should be tight. some get used more than others. slightly looser than the rest is ok. watch for the software while turning a knob to see if it jumps or twitches or even moves when youre not touching it. air duster can usually fix this but better to avoid.
make sure audio in/out and mic work. should probably test midi.

if all youre interested in is having pads for drumming etc and dont care about the maschine software go with a presonus atom. much cheaper and good pads.

maschine studio is an option. doesnt have line/mic in though. $200-250. guitar center insurance will replace it with an mk3 should anything happen. 3 years coverage for one is about $65.

>>114379116
>>114379531
I have to disagre. Mixing while producing makes sense. Mastering while mixing will ruin it in my opinion.
Mastering is getting your mix to a competitive loudness and dealing with the overall feel of the song, matching it with other songs of the album. It is like the final 5% of your song.
Just a few problems with "mastering while mixing" from the top of my head
>you are fucking up your headroom when loudness is your concern while mixing (loudness is easy as fuck to achieve when you mix correctly)
>mastering should be done with fresh ears, just like mixing should be done with fresh ears (produce > pause > mix > pause > master)

I would highly suggest you to watch the "clip to zero" production strategy on Youtube to get loudness even before your master. In simple terms the strategy is using a clipper on almost all your individual signals. You are shaving off unneccessary peaks in your signal/sound and if done right you won't even hear a difference (you could push it further if you like the sound of distortion). So because all these peaks in your individual signals are gone you are not only creating more headroom and saving db you are also letting your compressors and limiter on your master work way more efficient.

>>114380484
I used to produce and mix with a limiter, comp and EQ on my master (I liked to listen to my WIPs mastered) and, while the final product may sound fine, you're kind of bypassing a lot of the crucial production steps by doing it that way. For example, if you disabled the master chain on some of my old tracks certain things would sound wrong, like the snares transients would be 6dB louder than the rest of the mix, they'd just be relying on the master limiter to tame them, and there'd be parts that sound too empty because I'm relying on the master compressor to increase the level of the reverb etc. All of those things can, and should, be addressed in the production/mixing stages. You shouldn't be trying to fix mixing issues in the mastering stage.

the trick is to push your gain into a limiter. you're getting it loud with out worrying about headroom and the reason this is important is because by the end of the mix you have a track, that's basically mastered aka loud AND clear. the problem with separating the mix/master into stages (OR using a final limiter to push the volume) is that perceptually it will be harder to spot the problems if you're mixing very low. btw this is similar to clip-to-zero but instead I'm just using limiters on every track to pump volume in and limit peaks. also im pretty sure this is common practice with EDM artists as they're hitting crazy low LUFs because of how limited/gained each group is before hitting the master. i've also seen this process explained vaguely by serveral up and coming guys 2

Yes. The approach I described with the clipper would deal with those transients of the snare at the source, not at the end in the master. Your master compressor should also never do the heavy lifting.

>>114380771
You are not "mixing very low". Dude, if you leave around 6-8 db of headroom this is plenty loud to proper produce and mix.
So okay, you are using a limiter instead of a clipper on every track. I guess there is little difference in terms of sound. it is a similar approach. But you are still making your process more complicated than needed, because due to the fact that you are pushing every sound to 0 db. So what happens when your individuals tracks pushed to 0 db compound? You are compounding distortions. I know this is a style in EDM, getting this distorted sound, so I guess you are not worrying about it. But if you switch to other genres you'll have a hard time achieving a clean mix.

My suggestion is pushing those individual tracks to 0 db with a clipper or limiter like you. But you should not push the overall mix into 0 db, you leave around 6-8 db headroom going into the master. So why leave headroom? Because you can shape your overall mix with plugins on the master channel. Automations for your whole track, stereo imaging, mid/side EQ, normal EQ, saturation, compression, coloring EQ, multi-band copression... and then you push all of it into your final limiter to its limits.

as you push the sounds up toward 0db you can spot the problems or 'compounding distortions' in the mix. you then address them and continually push up each element based on what type of mix you are going for. btw this actually results in a cleaner mix because as you pump each element in gain you spot the problems faster. it forces you to hear your mix and say 'ok what should be louder? or quieter? or changed tonally? what i'm trying to avoid is giving myself the headroom then pushing a master limiter/comp/eq when their is still obvious problems in the mix. these problems that are better addressed at the source than by master plugins. idk how else to explain it.

I used to master with that much headroom and I was always frustrated with the results. just check out all the big DnB names like Noisia, Mefjus, Skrill etc and they all do this. they get clean, loud mixes because of this way of mixmastering. same goes for some hyperpop kids who initially learned EDM then transitioned (kek) into more of a rock/pop sound.

Brian Wilson was laying in bed, feeling a bit under the weather. He was just about to doze off when he heard a sports car pull into the driveway. The sound of the engine rumbling through the quiet neighborhood caused Brian to sit up in bed and listen.

He heard the car doors open and close, followed by the sound of footsteps approaching the house. Brian couldn't help but wonder who it could be at this hour.

As the footsteps grew louder, Brian's mind started racing. Could it be one of his old bandmates? He hadn't seen any of them in years.

Just as he was about to get out of bed to see who it was, he heard a knock on the door. Brian hesitated for a moment, still not feeling up to par. But eventually, he swung his legs over the side of the bed and made his way to the front door.

When he opened it, he was surprised to see Mike Love standing on his porch. "Hey Brian, hope I'm not interrupting anything," Mike said with a smile.

Brian couldn't help but smile back. It had been such a long time since they had seen each other. "No, not at all. Come on in," Brian replied, stepping aside to let Mike enter.

As they sat and caught up, Brian couldn't help but feel grateful for the unexpected visit from his old friend. It was just the lift he needed to brighten his day.

posts.com:
>Elvis Costello Live 1977 Chicago
>First generation pop-punk, British Power Pop
This has been released under the titles Armed and Dangerous, as well as Exit, but this is the actual soundboard recording used for the WXRT "Unconcert" broadcast in 1978. (Called Unconcert because it was sponsored by 7-Up, The "Un-Cola") Believe it or not, Tom Petty and The Heartbreakers were the opening act at this show. This was just before Elvis Costello and The Attractions made their debut on Saturday Night Live, subbing for The Sex Pistols who cancelled. (THANKS, MALCOLM!) My Aim is True had just been released, but This Year's Model was just a few months away. (Songs from TYM were played at this show)
When you listen to this concert, you'll understand immediately why Elvis Costello and The Attractions were considered a "Punk" band, and why the first generation of punk rockers adopted them as their own until 1980.

Again, no video. My apologies.

The following is the Don Cab context:

This all went down on Don Cab's last tour in 2000 and happened at The Middle East in Cambridge, MA. One of the dudes from Don Caballero got a big head and decided his band wouldn't play with any local opening bands. Apparently the booking people didn't get the memo, and the band Pizza was slated to play and the members were already unloading when Don Cab shows up. Damon of Don Cab talks to management and gets Pizza to clear out. Apparently Pizza didn't make a stink about because they got free drinks for the night, but the fans of Pizza were pretty pissed, and were chanting "PIZZA" for all of Don Cab's set while sporadically spitting and launching actual slices at the guys.

Tour diary of a Don Cab member that documents it:

Damn, what did you use to make this one?
That sci fi like synth in seccion 1 sounds very organic. It doesnt have much melodic content yet it manages to stay interesting and keep the attention thorougt the whole duration
Seccion 2 is very relaxing and at the same time it keeps a background tension with the background noise, which blends seemingly with seccion 3, which has nice leads
Seccion 4 has that cool sci fi synth again, and the percussion here is more driven. I also like the fast repeating sounds echoed in various instruments by the middle
Some cool pads in seccion 5 but to me it was the less interesting one for some reason
Seccion 6 has some nice rhythms and a cool sonic atmosphere. The repetitive melody reminds me of a circus, music box or caroussel that then degrades and fades into nothigness

Overall the progression work very well, nothing seems out of place and the transitions are very smooth
Oh and Im really intrigued to know what the scifi synth thing is, the sound and the possibilities it open are very cool

You are right, the portuguese guitar sounds sharper and doesnt flow as much. Its very interesting how music styles differ by culture

By the way, since you liked my track "foi dada a largada", I would rec the album Choro Frevado by Jacaré (a nickname that means alligator). He was well respected as an instrumentalist but only recorded one album by a music magazine well into middle age. You will find exactly one channel with his music on youtube, a channel that has lots of other brazilian folk gems. The videos of this record are split into side a and side b

Side a
https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=DF9KHFWUU7Y
Side b
https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=aVL2tMSFO5M

The choro frevado of the title means choro with influences of frevo, a folk genre from the northeast with fast march like drums and fast melodies played on brass usually and danced by men in colorful skirts holding colorful umbrellas

Jacaré plays cavaquinho. In samba, cavaquinho can be used as a rhythmical, almost percussive even instrument. But it can also be used as a soloing instrument, like Jacaré does here

In "foi dada a largada" I tried to play like a solo cavaquinho but still building the harmonic base a guitar allows

There is a trick you can do to test out your records without a record player. All you need is a sewing needle. If you don't have one, something like a safety pin will also work with a gentler touch. You need to find a continuous groove in the record (there are lots so take your pick) and GENTLY drag the needle, so that the point is dragging behind your hand, along the groove around the record. Since there is no amplification it will be VERY quiet but if you put your ear right by the record while you are doing this, you will hear the music play. Good luck!

posts.com:
Trans [Geffen, 1982]
Like almost everybody, I thought this was his dumbest gaffe since Journey Through the Past at first--his Devo buddies at least figured out that robots sound more lifelike if you program in some funkbeats. Granted, good old Joe Lala does add the occasional kerplunkety, but down beneath the vocodered quaver in which Young sings most of these silly sci-fi ditties they belong rhythmically to Billy Talbot, who could no more get on the one than lead a gamelan ensemble. Gradually, however, I figured out that robots also sound more lifelike if they're singing those grade-A elegiac folk melodies Young makes up when he's in the mood, because this is as tuneful as Comes a Time. Also realized that although Young's sci-fi may be simple, it's not silly--or maybe I realized that although it may be silly it's also charming. I'm sure you'll be pleased to learn that his unending search for romantic perfection is under study by an android company. A-
